/* CDPSE :: content/pbqs.js — CDPSE performance-based question database (30). */
window.CDPSE = window.CDPSE || {}; CDPSE.pbqs = CDPSE.pbqs || [];
CDPSE.pbqs.push.apply(CDPSE.pbqs, [
{"id":"PBQ-01","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B1","title":"Assigning the correct privacy roles","brief":"A SaaS company processes customer data on behalf of its enterprise clients, and also processes its own employees' data. The privacy office must correctly label each party before the record-of-processing documentation is finalized.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — PROCESSING RELATIONSHIP MAP","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>PARTY A:</span> Enterprise client — decides what customer data\n  is collected, why it is collected, and how long it is kept.\n<span class='cy'>PARTY B:</span> The SaaS company — hosts the platform and\n  processes customer data strictly per Party A's written instructions.\n<span class='cy'>PARTY C:</span> The SaaS company's HR department — decides\n  independently what employee data to collect and how to use it.\n<span class='dim'>Note: a named individual chairs the privacy program and reports\n  findings directly to the board.</span>","fields":[{"label":"What role does Party A hold with respect to the customer data?","hint":"Determines purposes and means","options":["Data processor","Data controller","Data subject"],"answer":1,"explain":"Party A decides the purposes and means of processing customer data, which is the defining test for a data controller. 'Data processor' is wrong because a processor acts only on another party's instructions, which describes Party B, not Party A. 'Data subject' is wrong because Party A is an organization directing the processing, not the individual the data is about."},{"label":"What role does Party B hold with respect to the same customer data?","hint":"Acts only on another's instructions","options":["Data controller","Data processor","Joint controller"],"answer":1,"explain":"Party B processes the data strictly per Party A's written instructions and has no independent decision-making authority over purposes or means, which is the definition of a data processor. 'Data controller' is wrong because Party B does not decide why or how the data is used. 'Joint controller' is wrong because joint control requires shared decision-making over purposes, which the exhibit explicitly says Party B does not have."},{"label":"What role does Party C hold with respect to employee data?","hint":"Independent decision-making over its own workforce data","options":["Data processor","Data controller","Sub-processor"],"answer":1,"explain":"Party C's HR department independently decides what employee data to collect and how to use it, which makes the company a data controller for that dataset, distinct from its processor role for Party A's customer data. 'Data processor' is wrong because Party C is not following another party's instructions here. 'Sub-processor' is wrong because there is no processor delegating work downstream to Party C in this relationship."},{"label":"Who should the privacy program's board-facing accountability rest with, per the note?","hint":"A named accountable individual, not a committee alone","options":["The named individual chairing the privacy program (e.g., the DPO)","Whichever department happens to generate the most data","No one; accountability is diffused across all departments equally"],"answer":0,"explain":"The named individual who chairs the privacy program and reports to the board holds the formal accountability role (such as a DPO), which is exactly what the note describes. 'Whichever department generates the most data' has no bearing on formal accountability structure. 'No one; accountability is diffused' contradicts the accountability principle that requires a clearly assigned, named responsible party."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-02","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A6","title":"Choosing the correct privacy artifact","brief":"A privacy program has three draft documents pending publication, and each must be routed to the correct audience and purpose.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DOCUMENT SET UNDER REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DOC 1:</span> A public-facing statement describing what personal\n  data is collected, why, and data-subject rights, posted on the website.\n<span class='cy'>DOC 2:</span> An internal, mandatory rule stating that all new\n  systems must undergo a privacy impact assessment before launch.\n<span class='cy'>DOC 3:</span> An internal, non-mandatory recommendation on how\n  engineers should structure consent-tagging metadata in code.","fields":[{"label":"What type of artifact is DOC 1?","hint":"External audience, transparency obligation","options":["Privacy policy","Privacy notice","Privacy guideline"],"answer":1,"explain":"A public-facing statement describing what data is collected and why, aimed at external data subjects, is a privacy notice, the transparency artifact required by most privacy laws. 'Privacy policy' is wrong because a policy is typically an internal governing rule, not the external transparency statement. 'Privacy guideline' is wrong because guidelines are non-mandatory internal recommendations, not public disclosures."},{"label":"What type of artifact is DOC 2?","hint":"Internal, mandatory rule","options":["Privacy notice","Privacy policy","Privacy guideline"],"answer":1,"explain":"An internal, mandatory rule requiring PIAs before launch is a privacy policy, since policies are the mandatory internal governance statements the organization must follow. 'Privacy notice' is wrong because notices are external-facing disclosures to data subjects, not internal mandates. 'Privacy guideline' is wrong because guidelines are optional recommendations, while DOC 2 is explicitly mandatory."},{"label":"What type of artifact is DOC 3?","hint":"Internal, non-mandatory, how-to detail","options":["Privacy policy","Privacy procedure","Privacy guideline"],"answer":2,"explain":"A non-mandatory, internal recommendation on how to structure consent-tagging metadata is a guideline, since guidelines suggest good practice without being enforceable requirements. 'Privacy policy' is wrong because it is explicitly non-mandatory, unlike a policy. 'Privacy procedure' is wrong because a procedure is normally a mandatory, step-by-step process, whereas DOC 3 is a discretionary recommendation."},{"label":"Which artifact must be revised first if a new data-subject right is added by an updated law?","hint":"External-facing transparency obligation","options":["DOC 3 (guideline)","DOC 1 (notice)","DOC 2 (policy)"],"answer":1,"explain":"A privacy notice must accurately reflect current data-subject rights for the public, so a new statutory right requires updating DOC 1 first to remain compliant with the transparency obligation. 'DOC 3 (guideline)' is an internal, optional document unrelated to statutory disclosure obligations. 'DOC 2 (policy)' may eventually need updates too, but the immediate legal transparency obligation is tied to the external notice, not the internal policy."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-03","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1A3","title":"Selecting the correct lawful basis","brief":"A retailer is evaluating four separate processing activities and must select the lawful basis that best supports each one under a GDPR-style framework.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — PROCESSING ACTIVITY LOG","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY 1:</span> Sending a customer their purchase receipt\n  and order status updates.\n<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY 2:</span> Sending optional marketing emails about\n  unrelated products to existing customers.\n<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY 3:</span> Reporting suspicious transactions to a\n  financial regulator as required by law.\n<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY 4:</span> Using fraud-detection analytics on transaction\n  data to protect the business and its customers from financial loss.","fields":[{"label":"What lawful basis best supports ACTIVITY 1?","hint":"Necessary to fulfill the purchase agreement","options":["Consent","Performance of a contract","Legal obligation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sending a receipt and order status is necessary to perform the purchase contract the customer entered into, making performance of a contract the correct basis. 'Consent' is unnecessary here because the processing is inherent to fulfilling an agreed transaction, not a separate opt-in choice. 'Legal obligation' is wrong because no external law mandates sending receipts; it is a contractual necessity, not a statutory one."},{"label":"What lawful basis best supports ACTIVITY 2?","hint":"Optional, unrelated marketing","options":["Performance of a contract","Consent","Legitimate interest"],"answer":1,"explain":"Optional marketing for unrelated products goes beyond the original transaction and is not required to fulfill any contract or law, so it requires the data subject's freely given consent. 'Performance of a contract' is wrong because unrelated marketing is not necessary to deliver the purchased goods or services. 'Legitimate interest' is a weaker fit here since unrelated marketing to existing customers typically requires an opt-in in a GDPR-style framework, especially where local e-marketing rules require consent."},{"label":"What lawful basis best supports ACTIVITY 3?","hint":"Mandated by external regulation","options":["Legal obligation","Consent","Legitimate interest"],"answer":0,"explain":"Reporting suspicious transactions because a law requires it is squarely a legal obligation, the basis that applies when processing is mandated by statute or regulation. 'Consent' is wrong because the customer cannot opt out of a legally mandated regulatory report. 'Legitimate interest' is wrong because the driver here is an external mandate, not the organization's own balanced interest."},{"label":"What lawful basis best supports ACTIVITY 4?","hint":"Balancing business protection against subject impact","options":["Legal obligation","Legitimate interest","Consent"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fraud-detection analytics to protect the business and customers, absent a specific legal mandate or contract term, is a classic legitimate-interest processing activity, provided a balancing test confirms it does not override the data subject's rights. 'Legal obligation' is wrong unless a specific law mandates this exact analytics activity, which is not stated. 'Consent' is generally impractical for fraud detection, since requiring opt-in would undermine the fraud-prevention purpose itself."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-04","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B4","title":"Handling a data-subject access request","brief":"An individual submits a verified request asking what personal data a company holds about them and requesting its deletion. The privacy team must route the request correctly.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DSAR INTAKE FORM","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUESTER:</span> Verified existing customer, identity confirmed\n  via account login.\n<span class='cy'>REQUEST TYPE:</span> (1) Access to all personal data held, and\n  (2) erasure of that data.\n<span class='cy'>COMPLICATING FACT:</span> The customer has an open, disputed\n  invoice and a legal retention obligation requires keeping billing\n  records for 7 years.","fields":[{"label":"What is the FIRST step before fulfilling either part of this request?","hint":"Confirm the requester is who they claim","options":["Immediately delete all records to comply quickly","Verify the requester's identity and the scope of data covered, which the form already confirms via login","Ignore the request until the invoice dispute is resolved"],"answer":1,"explain":"Verifying identity and scoping what data is covered is the mandatory first step before acting on any data-subject request, and the exhibit confirms this was done via account login. 'Immediately delete all records to comply quickly' skips identity verification and ignores the retention obligation entirely, risking a compliance violation. 'Ignore the request until the invoice dispute is resolved' improperly delays a rights request without lawful basis to do so."},{"label":"How should the access portion of the request be handled?","hint":"Access rights generally apply broadly","options":["Provide the individual a copy of their personal data as held, within the legally required timeframe","Refuse access because an invoice dispute exists","Provide only data the company feels comfortable sharing"],"answer":0,"explain":"The right of access generally entitles a verified data subject to a copy of their personal data within a statutory timeframe, regardless of an unrelated billing dispute. 'Refuse access because an invoice dispute exists' improperly conflates an unrelated commercial dispute with a data-subject right. 'Provide only data the company feels comfortable sharing' violates the completeness the access right requires, absent a specific legal exemption."},{"label":"How should the erasure portion of the request be handled given the legal retention obligation?","hint":"Erasure is not absolute when law requires retention","options":["Erase everything immediately to fully satisfy the request","Erase what is not subject to the legal retention obligation, but retain the billing records for the legally mandated 7 years and inform the requester of this exception","Deny the entire erasure request outright with no explanation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Erasure rights are not absolute; where a legal obligation to retain specific records exists, the correct approach is to erase what is not subject to that obligation while retaining the legally required billing records and clearly explaining the exception to the requester. 'Erase everything immediately' would violate the statutory retention requirement for billing records. 'Deny the entire erasure request outright with no explanation' improperly denies erasure of the non-exempt data and fails the transparency obligation to explain the partial exception."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-05","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B5","title":"Determining breach notification obligations","brief":"A cloud misconfiguration exposed a database containing customer email addresses and hashed passwords for 72 hours before discovery. Legal and the privacy office must decide on notification.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — INCIDENT SUMMARY","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>EXPOSURE:</span> Email addresses and salted, strongly hashed\n  passwords for approximately 40,000 customers.\n<span class='cy'>ACCESS LOGS:</span> Confirm the bucket was publicly listable\n  and at least one unknown external IP accessed the file listing.\n<span class='cy'>REGULATORY CONTEXT:</span> Applicable law requires notifying\n  the regulator \"without undue delay\" when a breach is likely to\n  result in a risk to individuals' rights and freedoms.","fields":[{"label":"Does this incident meet the threshold for regulator notification under the stated standard?","hint":"Apply the risk-based test, not a strict data-type rule","options":["No, because passwords were hashed so there is no risk at all","Yes, likely — confirmed unauthorized access to personal data creates a plausible risk to individuals even with hashing in place","Notification is never required unless plaintext passwords are exposed"],"answer":1,"explain":"Confirmed external access to a dataset of email addresses and hashed passwords creates a plausible risk of harm, such as credential-stuffing or phishing using the exposed emails, meeting a 'likely to result in a risk' threshold even though the passwords were hashed. 'No, because passwords were hashed so there is no risk at all' overstates the protection hashing provides and ignores the exposed email addresses and confirmed access. 'Notification is never required unless plaintext passwords are exposed' misstates the legal standard, which is risk-based, not limited to a single data type."},{"label":"What does \"without undue delay\" require of the notification timeline?","hint":"Prompt action, not indefinite delay for a perfect investigation","options":["Notification can wait indefinitely until the investigation is 100% complete","Notification should occur promptly once the risk is known, often within a defined regulatory window (e.g., 72 hours), even if some investigation details are still developing","There is no timeline; notification is entirely discretionary"],"answer":1,"explain":"\"Without undue delay\" generally means notifying promptly, often within a specific regulatory window, once the organization becomes aware the breach meets the risk threshold, even while some investigative details are still being finalized. 'Notification can wait indefinitely until the investigation is 100% complete' misreads the standard, which does not permit open-ended delay. 'There is no timeline; notification is entirely discretionary' contradicts the explicit regulatory deadline concept described in the standard."},{"label":"Beyond the regulator, who else may need to be notified given the exposed email addresses?","hint":"Data subjects may face a specific, actionable risk","options":["No one else; regulator notification alone is always sufficient","The affected individuals, since they can take protective action such as changing passwords or watching for phishing","Only the company's own executive team, with no external notice"],"answer":1,"explain":"When individuals face an actionable risk, such as phishing using their exposed email addresses, direct notification lets them take protective steps like changing reused passwords, which is a common companion obligation to regulator notification. 'No one else; regulator notification alone is always sufficient' ignores that many laws require direct data-subject notification when risk is high enough. 'Only the company's own executive team, with no external notice' fails both the regulatory and individual notification obligations entirely."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-06","format":1,"domain":1,"obj":"1B2","title":"Assessing vendor privacy risk before onboarding","brief":"Procurement wants to onboard a new marketing analytics vendor that will receive a data export containing customer identifiers, and the privacy office must evaluate the arrangement.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — VENDOR PRIVACY REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>VENDOR ROLE:</span> Processes customer identifiers strictly to\n  generate aggregate marketing reports per our specifications.\n<span class='cy'>CONTRACT DRAFT:</span> Does not yet include a data processing\n  addendum (DPA) or sub-processor disclosure clause.\n<span class='cy'>VENDOR CLAIM:</span> \"We are fully compliant\" (no supporting\n  documentation provided).","fields":[{"label":"What role does this vendor hold, and what contractual artifact is missing?","hint":"Instructed processing needs a specific contract clause","options":["The vendor is a controller; no artifact is required","The vendor is a processor; a data processing addendum (DPA) defining obligations and sub-processor terms is missing and should be required","The vendor is a data subject; only a notice is required"],"answer":1,"explain":"Since the vendor processes data strictly per the company's specifications, it is a processor, and a DPA defining processing obligations, security requirements, and sub-processor disclosure is the standard, often legally required, contractual artifact that is currently missing. 'The vendor is a controller; no artifact is required' misclassifies the role and ignores contractual necessity entirely. 'The vendor is a data subject; only a notice is required' fundamentally misunderstands the vendor's role in this processing relationship."},{"label":"How should the unsupported \"fully compliant\" claim be treated?","hint":"Verify, do not simply accept, assurance claims","options":["Accept it at face value and proceed with onboarding immediately","Request independent evidence, such as an audit report or security questionnaire responses, before relying on the claim","Reject the vendor automatically without further discussion"],"answer":1,"explain":"An unverified compliance claim should be substantiated with independent evidence, such as an audit report, certification, or completed security/privacy questionnaire, before the organization relies on it. 'Accept it at face value and proceed with onboarding immediately' repeats the classic due-diligence failure of trusting unverified marketing language. 'Reject the vendor automatically without further discussion' is premature; the correct step is to request evidence, not to abandon the vendor relationship outright."},{"label":"What ongoing obligation continues after the contract is signed?","hint":"Vendor risk does not end at signature","options":["None; the signed contract fully discharges all privacy risk","Periodic monitoring of the vendor's privacy and security posture and re-assessment on material changes (e.g., new sub-processors)","Only the vendor's own internal obligation, with no visibility required by the company"],"answer":1,"explain":"Vendor privacy risk management is ongoing; the company should periodically monitor the vendor's posture and reassess when material changes occur, such as new sub-processors or a security incident. 'None; the signed contract fully discharges all privacy risk' incorrectly treats the contract as a one-time control rather than part of continuous third-party risk management. 'Only the vendor's own internal obligation, with no visibility required' abdicates the company's own accountability for data it has entrusted to a processor."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-07","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A2","title":"Scoping a DPIA for a new initiative","brief":"A retailer plans to deploy in-store cameras with facial-analysis software to estimate customer demographics for advertising. The privacy team must decide whether a DPIA is required and what it should cover.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — INITIATIVE INTAKE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>INITIATIVE:</span> Cameras analyze facial images in real time to\n  estimate age range and gender for anonymized ad targeting analytics.\n<span class='cy'>DATA TYPE:</span> Facial images are a form of biometric data\n  under many privacy laws, even if not stored long-term.\n<span class='cy'>SCALE:</span> Deployed across 150 stores, processing the faces\n  of all visitors, not just opted-in participants.","fields":[{"label":"Is a DPIA required for this initiative?","hint":"Large-scale biometric processing without opt-in is a high-risk trigger","options":["No, because the output is only aggregate, anonymized statistics","Yes, because large-scale processing of biometric data on non-consenting visitors is a recognized high-risk trigger","No, because cameras are a physical security measure, not a privacy concern"],"answer":1,"explain":"Large-scale processing of biometric data, especially of individuals who have not opted in, is a classic DPIA trigger under most privacy frameworks, regardless of whether the eventual output is aggregated. 'No, because the output is only aggregate, anonymized statistics' wrongly focuses on the output rather than the risk created during the interim biometric processing stage. 'No, because cameras are a physical security measure, not a privacy concern' mischaracterizes a facial-analysis system as mere physical security, ignoring the biometric data being processed."},{"label":"What should the DPIA specifically evaluate given the biometric data type?","hint":"Necessity, proportionality, and safeguards for sensitive data","options":["Only the marginal cost of the camera hardware across 150 stores","The necessity and proportionality of processing biometric data, safeguards limiting retention/identification, and risk to non-consenting visitors","The visual design and placement of the advertising displays"],"answer":1,"explain":"A DPIA for this initiative must evaluate whether biometric processing is necessary and proportionate to the advertising goal, what safeguards limit retention or re-identification, and the risk to visitors who never opted in. 'Only the marginal cost of the camera hardware' is a procurement consideration, not a privacy risk evaluation. 'The visual design and placement of the advertising displays' is a marketing/UX concern unrelated to the privacy risk assessment."},{"label":"What is the appropriate outcome if the DPIA identifies a high residual risk that cannot be sufficiently mitigated?","hint":"Some frameworks require escalation before proceeding","options":["Proceed with deployment regardless, since the DPIA is only advisory","Consult the relevant supervisory authority or halt/modify the initiative before proceeding, per the applicable framework's prior-consultation requirement","Quietly proceed but stop documenting the assessment"],"answer":1,"explain":"When a DPIA reveals high residual risk that cannot be adequately mitigated, many frameworks require prior consultation with the supervisory authority, or modification/halting of the initiative, before proceeding. 'Proceed with deployment regardless, since the DPIA is only advisory' misunderstands that unmitigated high risk can trigger a mandatory consultation or hold requirement, not a purely advisory outcome. 'Quietly proceed but stop documenting the assessment' both ignores the risk and destroys the accountability record the DPIA is meant to create."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-08","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A3","title":"Identifying the privacy threat in each scenario","brief":"An internal audit surfaced three situations, and the privacy team must correctly name the specific privacy threat or harm each one represents before selecting a response.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — THREAT IDENTIFICATION LOG","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CASE 1:</span> A dataset of \"anonymized\" location pings, when\n  combined with public social media check-ins, can identify specific\n  individuals' home addresses.\n<span class='cy'>CASE 2:</span> Customer support call recordings, collected solely\n  for quality assurance, are later reused to train a marketing\n  recommendation model without new notice or consent.\n<span class='cy'>CASE 3:</span> A signup form collects a user's full date of birth,\n  home address, and mother's maiden name to create a newsletter account.","fields":[{"label":"What privacy threat does CASE 1 represent?","hint":"Combining datasets defeats anonymization","options":["Re-identification through data linkage","Excessive collection","Unauthorized third-party disclosure"],"answer":0,"explain":"Combining supposedly anonymized data with an external dataset to re-identify individuals is the classic re-identification-through-linkage threat, which undermines claims of true anonymization. 'Excessive collection' is not the issue here since the location data itself may have been reasonably scoped; the harm arises from linkage, not collection volume. 'Unauthorized third-party disclosure' is wrong because no third party disclosure by the company is described; the risk comes from combining data the individual or others made available separately."},{"label":"What privacy threat does CASE 2 represent?","hint":"Data used beyond its original stated purpose","options":["Secondary use without appropriate notice or basis","Data retention beyond policy","Weak authentication controls"],"answer":0,"explain":"Reusing call recordings collected for quality assurance to train a marketing model, without new notice or a valid basis, is secondary use, a core purpose-limitation violation. 'Data retention beyond policy' is not indicated, since the issue is the new purpose, not necessarily how long the recordings were kept. 'Weak authentication controls' is unrelated; this scenario is about purpose limitation, not access security."},{"label":"What privacy threat does CASE 3 represent?","hint":"Collecting more than the purpose requires","options":["Excessive collection relative to the stated newsletter purpose","Cross-border transfer risk","Insufficient encryption at rest"],"answer":0,"explain":"Collecting full date of birth, home address, and a security-question-style answer just to sign up for a newsletter is excessive collection relative to the minimal purpose stated, violating data minimization. 'Cross-border transfer risk' is not indicated anywhere in the scenario, which describes only what is collected. 'Insufficient encryption at rest' may or may not be true but is not the threat being illustrated, which is about collection scope, not storage security."},{"label":"Which of the three cases most directly violates the principle of data minimization?","hint":"Focus on collection scope versus purpose","options":["CASE 1","CASE 2","CASE 3"],"answer":2,"explain":"CASE 3 collects far more sensitive data than a newsletter signup requires, which is the textbook definition of a data-minimization violation. 'CASE 1' is primarily a re-identification/anonymization failure, not a minimization issue. 'CASE 2' is primarily a purpose-limitation and secondary-use issue, not a minimization issue."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-09","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2A4","title":"Choosing the privacy risk response","brief":"The privacy risk register lists three identified risks pending a treatment decision at the quarterly risk committee meeting.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — RISK TREATMENT QUEUE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>RISK A:</span> A planned feature would collect precise geolocation\n  for a use case that provides negligible business value; leadership\n  agrees to cancel the feature.\n<span class='cy'>RISK B:</span> A legacy system cannot be fully remediated to meet\n  encryption standards for 18 months; leadership signs a formal,\n  time-boxed memo acknowledging the exposure.\n<span class='cy'>RISK C:</span> A cross-border data flow risk is addressed by\n  purchasing a cyber/privacy liability insurance policy covering\n  regulatory fines up to a set limit.","fields":[{"label":"What risk response does RISK A represent?","hint":"Eliminating the risk-generating activity","options":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Canceling the feature entirely removes the activity that would have created the geolocation privacy risk, which is risk avoidance. 'Risk mitigation' would mean reducing the risk while still pursuing the feature, which does not match a cancellation decision. 'Risk transfer' would shift impact to a third party, which canceling a feature does not do."},{"label":"What risk response does RISK B represent?","hint":"Formal, documented decision to leave the exposure in place temporarily","options":["Risk acceptance","Risk avoidance","Risk mitigation"],"answer":0,"explain":"A formal, time-boxed memo acknowledging the exposure while it remains unremediated is risk acceptance, since leadership is knowingly living with the risk for a defined period. 'Risk avoidance' would require eliminating the risk-bearing activity, which is not happening here. 'Risk mitigation' would require actively reducing the risk now, but the scenario describes tolerating it, not reducing it."},{"label":"What risk response does RISK C represent?","hint":"Shifting financial consequence to a third party","options":["Risk mitigation","Risk avoidance","Risk transfer"],"answer":2,"explain":"Purchasing insurance to cover regulatory fines shifts the financial consequence of the risk to a third-party insurer, which is risk transfer. 'Risk mitigation' would involve directly reducing the likelihood or impact of the cross-border risk through controls, not insuring against it. 'Risk avoidance' would mean eliminating the cross-border flow entirely, which the scenario does not describe."},{"label":"Which response, if any, still requires active residual-risk monitoring going forward?","hint":"Acceptance does not mean the risk vanishes","options":["RISK A only, since avoided risks must still be monitored","RISK B, since an accepted, time-boxed exposure must be tracked to its resolution date","None of the risks require any further monitoring once treated"],"answer":1,"explain":"RISK B's time-boxed acceptance explicitly requires monitoring toward the 18-month remediation deadline, since an accepted risk is still a live exposure, not a resolved one. 'RISK A only, since avoided risks must still be monitored' is incorrect because an avoided risk, by cancelling the feature, removes the exposure and requires no further tracking of that specific risk. 'None of the risks require any further monitoring once treated' is wrong because an accepted risk, unlike an avoided or effectively insured one, remains active and must be tracked."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-10","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B1","title":"Mapping the control to the governing framework","brief":"An auditor is reviewing which authoritative reference best supports three specific privacy control statements documented in the control library.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONTROL-TO-FRAMEWORK MAPPING","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CONTROL 1:</span> \"The organization shall implement the five\n  functions of Identify-P, Govern-P, Control-P, Communicate-P, and\n  Protect-P to manage privacy risk.\"\n<span class='cy'>CONTROL 2:</span> \"The organization maintains an information\n  security management system extended with privacy-specific\n  controls for PII controllers and processors.\"\n<span class='cy'>CONTROL 3:</span> \"Data subjects have the right to erasure,\n  absent an overriding legal ground, under Article 17.\"","fields":[{"label":"Which framework does CONTROL 1 reference?","hint":"Named functions unique to one framework","options":["ISO/IEC 27701","NIST Privacy Framework","GDPR"],"answer":1,"explain":"Identify-P, Govern-P, Control-P, Communicate-P, and Protect-P are the five core functions unique to the NIST Privacy Framework, directly matching CONTROL 1. 'ISO/IEC 27701' uses a management-system clause structure, not these named functions. 'GDPR' is a regulation with articles and principles, not a functions-based framework like this."},{"label":"Which framework does CONTROL 2 reference?","hint":"Management-system extension for PII controllers/processors","options":["NIST Privacy Framework","ISO/IEC 27701","GDPR"],"answer":1,"explain":"ISO/IEC 27701 is specifically the privacy information management system extension to ISO/IEC 27001, built for PII controllers and processors, matching CONTROL 2 exactly. 'NIST Privacy Framework' uses the five named functions, not an ISMS extension structure. 'GDPR' is a legal regulation, not a management-system standard with a certifiable ISMS extension."},{"label":"Which framework does CONTROL 3 reference?","hint":"Numbered legal article granting a data-subject right","options":["ISO/IEC 27701","NIST Privacy Framework","GDPR"],"answer":2,"explain":"The right to erasure under a numbered Article 17 is a direct GDPR reference, since GDPR articles enumerate specific data-subject rights and obligations. 'ISO/IEC 27701' does not use numbered legal articles granting statutory rights; it is a management-system standard. 'NIST Privacy Framework' is a voluntary risk-management framework, not a source of enforceable legal rights like Article 17."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-11","format":2,"domain":2,"obj":"2B4","title":"Selecting the right compliance monitoring metric","brief":"The compliance team wants a small dashboard of metrics that meaningfully shows whether the privacy program is operating effectively, not just busy.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CANDIDATE COMPLIANCE METRICS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>METRIC 1:</span> Percentage of DSARs completed within the\n  legally required timeframe, trended quarterly.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC 2:</span> Total number of privacy training slides created\n  this year.\n<span class='cy'>METRIC 3:</span> Number of high-risk DPIA findings remediated\n  versus identified, trended quarterly.","fields":[{"label":"Which metrics are most meaningful for demonstrating ongoing program effectiveness?","hint":"Outcome-based and legally anchored, not busywork counts","options":["Metric 2 only","Metrics 1 and 3, since they tie directly to legal obligations and risk remediation outcomes","All three are equally meaningful"],"answer":1,"explain":"DSAR timeliness and DPIA-finding remediation rates are outcome-based measures directly tied to legal compliance and actual risk reduction, making them the most meaningful metrics for governance. 'Metric 2 only' counts training material volume, which says nothing about whether obligations are actually being met. 'All three are equally meaningful' incorrectly elevates a raw activity count to the same value as compliance-outcome metrics."},{"label":"Why is Metric 2 a weak standalone compliance indicator?","hint":"Volume of content is not the same as effectiveness","options":["Because it reflects effort/output volume, not whether training changed behavior or reduced risk","Because slide counts are impossible to measure accurately","Because training is not part of the privacy program"],"answer":0,"explain":"A slide count measures how much content was produced, not whether staff understood it or whether privacy incidents caused by human error decreased, so it says little about actual program effectiveness. 'Because slide counts are impossible to measure accurately' is false; slide counts are trivially countable, they are just not meaningful. 'Because training is not part of the privacy program' is incorrect, training and awareness is a recognized program component, the issue is the specific metric chosen."},{"label":"If Metric 3 shows remediation consistently lagging identification, what should the privacy team do?","hint":"A widening gap signals a resourcing or process problem","options":["Ignore the gap since DPIAs are only advisory","Investigate the root cause (e.g., resourcing, prioritization) and escalate to governance for corrective action","Stop performing DPIAs to avoid generating more findings"],"answer":1,"explain":"A persistent gap between identified and remediated high-risk findings signals an operational problem, such as insufficient resourcing or unclear ownership, that should be investigated and escalated to governance for corrective action. 'Ignore the gap since DPIAs are only advisory' misunderstands that unremediated high-risk findings represent live, unmanaged privacy risk. 'Stop performing DPIAs to avoid generating more findings' perversely removes the visibility needed to manage risk at all, rather than fixing the remediation bottleneck."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-12","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A2","title":"Building the data inventory and map","brief":"A company is building its first data inventory and dataflow map and must correctly sequence the discovery activities.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DISCOVERY ACTIVITY LIST","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY X:</span> Interview business-unit owners and scan\n  systems to identify what personal data exists and where.\n<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY Y:</span> Classify each discovered data element by\n  sensitivity and regulatory category.\n<span class='cy'>ACTIVITY Z:</span> Diagram how classified data moves between\n  systems, third parties, and geographies.","fields":[{"label":"Which activity must occur FIRST?","hint":"You cannot classify or map what you haven't found","options":["Activity Y (classify)","Activity X (discover)","Activity Z (map flows)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Discovery, identifying what personal data exists and where it resides, must happen first, since neither classification nor flow-mapping is possible without first knowing what data exists. 'Activity Y (classify)' cannot occur before the data elements to classify have even been identified. 'Activity Z (map flows)' requires knowing what data exists and its classification before flows can be meaningfully diagrammed."},{"label":"Which activity logically follows discovery?","hint":"Sensitivity must be known before flows are prioritized","options":["Activity Z (map flows)","Activity Y (classify)","Repeat discovery indefinitely with no next step"],"answer":1,"explain":"After discovery, classifying each data element by sensitivity and regulatory category comes next, since flow-mapping is most useful once you know which flows carry higher-risk data. 'Activity Z (map flows)' before classification would treat all data flows as equally important, missing the risk-prioritization benefit classification provides. 'Repeat discovery indefinitely with no next step' ignores that discovery is a bounded activity meant to feed into classification and mapping."},{"label":"Which activity should occur LAST in this sequence?","hint":"Visualizing movement once you know what and how sensitive it is","options":["Activity X (discover)","Activity Y (classify)","Activity Z (map flows)"],"answer":2,"explain":"Mapping how classified data moves between systems, third parties, and geographies logically comes last, once the data has been found and classified, so the map reflects accurate risk context. 'Activity X (discover)' is the necessary first step and cannot come last. 'Activity Y (classify)' must precede flow-mapping to give the map meaningful risk context, so it cannot be the final step either."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-13","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A5","title":"Applying purpose and use limitation","brief":"A ride-sharing app collected precise trip-location data to calculate fares and provide navigation. A new internal proposal wants to reuse that same data for an unrelated purpose.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — REUSE PROPOSAL","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ORIGINAL PURPOSE (per privacy notice):</span> Calculate fares\n  and provide turn-by-turn navigation during active trips.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSAL:</span> Sell aggregated, but still individually\n  traceable, trip-location histories to a real-estate analytics\n  firm for neighborhood valuation modeling.\n<span class='dim'>No new consent has been obtained; the privacy notice was not\n  updated to mention this new purpose.</span>","fields":[{"label":"Does the proposal comply with the purpose-limitation principle as described?","hint":"New, incompatible purpose without a fresh basis","options":["Yes, because the data was already lawfully collected","No, because selling the data for real-estate analytics is a new purpose incompatible with the original notice, without a new lawful basis or updated notice","Yes, because aggregation makes any reuse automatically acceptable"],"answer":1,"explain":"Purpose limitation requires that data be used only for the purpose it was collected for, or a compatible one; selling individually traceable location histories for real-estate analytics is a materially different, incompatible purpose that was never disclosed or consented to. 'Yes, because the data was already lawfully collected' incorrectly assumes lawful collection permits unlimited future reuse. 'Yes, because aggregation makes any reuse automatically acceptable' is wrong because the exhibit specifies the data remains individually traceable, so aggregation here does not neutralize the privacy risk."},{"label":"What would be the MINIMUM step required before this reuse could proceed lawfully?","hint":"Transparency and a valid basis for the new purpose","options":["Nothing; internal proposals do not require any privacy review","Update the privacy notice to disclose the new purpose and establish a valid lawful basis (e.g., new consent) for it","Simply rename the internal project so it no longer references the original navigation purpose"],"answer":1,"explain":"At minimum, the organization would need to update its privacy notice to disclose the new purpose and establish a valid lawful basis, such as fresh consent, before using the data this way. 'Nothing; internal proposals do not require any privacy review' ignores the clear purpose-limitation violation identified. 'Simply rename the internal project' is a cosmetic change that does nothing to address the underlying transparency and lawful-basis gap."},{"label":"If true anonymization (not just aggregation) could be achieved such that individuals are no longer identifiable, how would the analysis change?","hint":"Anonymized data generally falls outside personal-data scope","options":["The analysis would not change at all; anonymization is irrelevant to purpose limitation","Properly and irreversibly anonymized data generally falls outside the scope of personal data protections, potentially permitting the new use without the original purpose limitation applying","Anonymization would make the original navigation purpose retroactively invalid"],"answer":1,"explain":"If the data is properly and irreversibly anonymized such that re-identification is not reasonably possible, it generally falls outside the definition of personal data, so purpose-limitation rules built around personal data would no longer directly restrict this specific reuse. 'The analysis would not change at all' ignores that most privacy laws' scope depends on data being identifiable. 'Anonymization would make the original navigation purpose retroactively invalid' is a nonsensical outcome unrelated to how anonymization actually affects legal scope."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-14","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B3","title":"Selecting the cross-border transfer mechanism","brief":"A US-based company wants to transfer EU customer personal data to its US processing subsidiary, and the privacy team must select the correct transfer mechanism for each scenario.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — TRANSFER SCENARIOS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SCENARIO 1:</span> Transfer to a country the EU has formally\n  recognized as providing an equivalent level of data protection.\n<span class='cy'>SCENARIO 2:</span> Transfer to the US subsidiary, a jurisdiction\n  without a general adequacy decision, using a pre-approved,\n  standardized contractual template between exporter and importer.\n<span class='cy'>SCENARIO 3:</span> Transfer within the same corporate group\n  across multiple countries, governed by an internally approved,\n  legally binding intra-group privacy policy.","fields":[{"label":"What transfer mechanism applies to SCENARIO 1?","hint":"A formal recognition of equivalence","options":["Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)","Adequacy decision","Binding Corporate Rules (BCRs)"],"answer":1,"explain":"A formal determination that a country provides an equivalent level of data protection is an adequacy decision, which permits transfers without additional safeguards. 'Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)' are used precisely when no adequacy decision exists, which contradicts SCENARIO 1. 'Binding Corporate Rules (BCRs)' govern intra-group transfers under an internal framework, not a country-level adequacy finding."},{"label":"What transfer mechanism applies to SCENARIO 2?","hint":"Pre-approved template contract terms","options":["Adequacy decision","Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)","Consent of each data subject for every transfer"],"answer":1,"explain":"A pre-approved, standardized contractual template used between exporter and importer to legitimize a transfer absent adequacy is precisely what Standard Contractual Clauses are designed for. 'Adequacy decision' does not apply here since the scenario explicitly states no general adequacy decision exists. 'Consent of each data subject for every transfer' does not scale operationally and is not what SCCs represent; SCCs are a contractual mechanism, not individual consent."},{"label":"What transfer mechanism applies to SCENARIO 3?","hint":"Internal, legally binding, intra-group framework","options":["Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)","Binding Corporate Rules (BCRs)","Adequacy decision"],"answer":1,"explain":"An internally approved, legally binding privacy framework governing transfers within the same corporate group across multiple countries is the definition of Binding Corporate Rules. 'Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)' are bilateral contracts typically used between separate exporting and importing entities, not an overarching intra-group framework. 'Adequacy decision' is a country-level determination made by a regulator, not an internally created corporate framework."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-15","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B6","title":"Selecting the correct destruction or de-identification method","brief":"An organization is retiring several data assets and must select the technically correct disposal or de-identification method for each based on the medium and future need.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DISPOSAL DECISION LOG","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>ASSET 1:</span> Cloud-hosted encrypted volume that must be\n  rendered permanently unreadable quickly, without physical media\n  destruction (data is spread across shared infrastructure).\n<span class='cy'>ASSET 2:</span> Physical hard drives being retired from an\n  on-premises server, with no future reuse planned.\n<span class='cy'>ASSET 3:</span> A dataset needed for aggregate trend analytics\n  where individual-level detail is no longer required, but the\n  data must still exist and be usable in de-identified form.","fields":[{"label":"What is the BEST method for ASSET 1?","hint":"Destroy the key, not the shared physical media","options":["Physical degaussing of the shared storage array","Crypto-shredding — securely destroying the encryption keys so the encrypted data becomes permanently unreadable","Simply deleting the file pointer while leaving the encrypted blocks in place"],"answer":1,"explain":"Crypto-shredding, destroying the encryption keys, renders encrypted data permanently unreadable without needing to physically destroy shared cloud infrastructure, matching the constraint described. 'Physical degaussing of the shared storage array' is impractical and destructive on shared multi-tenant infrastructure. 'Simply deleting the file pointer while leaving the encrypted blocks in place' does not reliably prevent recovery and is not equivalent to actual secure destruction."},{"label":"What is the BEST method for ASSET 2?","hint":"Physical media with no future use","options":["Crypto-shredding only, since encryption keys are sufficient for physical drives too","Physical destruction (e.g., shredding or degaussing) or certified secure wipe of the physical drives, since no reuse is planned","Simply relabeling the drives and placing them in storage"],"answer":1,"explain":"For physical drives being permanently retired with no reuse planned, physical destruction or a certified secure wipe is the appropriate method, ensuring the data cannot be recovered from the media itself. 'Crypto-shredding only' is not reliable here unless the drives were fully encrypted with a securely destroyed key; the scenario does not establish that, making physical destruction or certified wipe the safer choice for retiring physical media. 'Simply relabeling the drives and placing them in storage' does not dispose of the data at all and leaves it recoverable."},{"label":"What is the BEST approach for ASSET 3?","hint":"Data must remain usable, just not at the individual level","options":["Anonymization or de-identification (e.g., aggregation, generalization) that removes individual-level identifiability while preserving analytical utility","Full destruction of the dataset, since it is no longer needed in its original form","Encryption alone, with the individual-level detail left fully intact"],"answer":0,"explain":"Since the data must remain usable for aggregate analytics but individual-level identifiability is no longer needed, anonymization or de-identification techniques that strip identifying detail while preserving aggregate utility are the correct approach. 'Full destruction of the dataset' would eliminate the data the business still needs for trend analytics. 'Encryption alone, with the individual-level detail left fully intact' does not reduce identifiability at all; encryption protects confidentiality in storage/transit but does not de-identify the data for this use case."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-16","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A6","title":"Governing an AI training dataset across the life cycle","brief":"A company wants to use historical customer support tickets, which contain personal data, to fine-tune an internal AI model. The privacy team must apply life-cycle controls before approval.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — AI DATASET INTAKE","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SOURCE DATA:</span> Two years of support tickets containing\n  names, emails, and free-text descriptions of customer issues.\n<span class='cy'>ORIGINAL NOTICE:</span> Told customers data would be used\n  \"to resolve your support request and improve our service.\"\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED USE:</span> Fine-tune a generative AI model that may\n  later produce customer-facing responses, with a risk that\n  training data could be memorized and regurgitated verbatim.","fields":[{"label":"Does the original notice reasonably cover this proposed AI training use?","hint":"\"Improve our service\" is broad, but memorization risk is a new consideration","options":["Yes, without qualification, because \"improve our service\" covers any conceivable future use of the data","Arguably yes for general service improvement, but the specific risk of verbatim memorization and disclosure of personal data warrants a fresh privacy review and possibly updated notice","No, because AI training can never be considered a service-improvement activity"],"answer":1,"explain":"While broad service-improvement language may cover general analytics, the specific and material risk that an AI model could memorize and regurgitate personal data verbatim to other customers is a new, foreseeable risk that a reasonable data subject likely did not anticipate, warranting a fresh privacy assessment and likely a notice update. 'Yes, without qualification' overreads a general improvement clause to cover an unforeseen and materially different risk. 'No, because AI training can never be considered a service-improvement activity' is too absolute; the real issue is the specific memorization/disclosure risk, not that AI training categorically falls outside the clause."},{"label":"What data-minimization step should be applied before training begins?","hint":"Reduce identifiability before it enters the model","options":["Use the raw ticket text unmodified, including names and emails, to preserve maximum data fidelity","Apply de-identification or redaction of direct identifiers (names, emails) in the training data where feasible, consistent with the model's purpose","Skip minimization since the model is only used internally"],"answer":1,"explain":"Redacting or de-identifying direct identifiers before training reduces the risk that the model memorizes and later exposes personal data, while still preserving the substance needed for the model's purpose. 'Use the raw ticket text unmodified' maximizes the exact memorization risk the scenario flags as a concern. 'Skip minimization since the model is only used internally' ignores that internal use does not eliminate the risk of memorized data surfacing in later outputs or through model access."},{"label":"What ongoing control addresses the risk that the deployed model could still regurgitate personal data despite redaction efforts?","hint":"Defense in depth after training, not just before","options":["No further control is needed once redaction is applied before training","Output monitoring/filtering and periodic testing for memorized personal data leakage in model outputs after deployment","Simply deleting the original support tickets after training with no further review of model behavior"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because redaction can be imperfect and models can still memorize residual patterns, ongoing output monitoring and periodic testing for personal-data leakage in generated responses is a necessary defense-in-depth control after deployment. 'No further control is needed once redaction is applied before training' assumes redaction is perfect, which is an unsafe assumption for generative models. 'Simply deleting the original support tickets after training with no further review' addresses the source data but does nothing to catch memorization risk already baked into the trained model."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-17","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3B2","title":"Evaluating a third-party data-sharing request","brief":"A business partner requests a bulk export of customer contact and purchase-history data to run a joint marketing campaign, and the privacy team must evaluate the request against life-cycle governance requirements.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SHARING REQUEST","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUEST:</span> Full export of customer name, email, phone, and\n  full purchase history for a joint marketing campaign.\n<span class='cy'>ORIGINAL NOTICE:</span> States data may be shared with\n  \"marketing partners for co-branded campaigns, where the customer\n  has opted in to partner marketing.\"\n<span class='cy'>CURRENT STATE:</span> Only 30% of the requested customer records\n  have an affirmative partner-marketing opt-in on file.","fields":[{"label":"What is the correct scope of data that may be shared under the existing notice and consent state?","hint":"Consent status gates who can be included","options":["The full requested export, since the notice generally allows partner marketing sharing","Only the subset of records (the 30%) with an affirmative partner-marketing opt-in on file","None of the data, since any partner sharing is always prohibited"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because the notice conditions partner-marketing sharing on an affirmative opt-in, only the 30% of records with that opt-in on file may lawfully be included in the export. 'The full requested export' would share data for the 70% of customers who never opted in to partner marketing, violating the notice's own condition. 'None of the data, since any partner sharing is always prohibited' is incorrect because the notice explicitly permits sharing for the opted-in subset."},{"label":"What data-minimization consideration applies even to the eligible 30% subset?","hint":"Full purchase history may exceed campaign needs","options":["Share the full purchase history regardless of campaign relevance, since it was already collected","Evaluate whether the full purchase history is necessary for the campaign, or whether a reduced field set would suffice","Purchase history is never shareable with any partner under any circumstance"],"answer":1,"explain":"Even for eligible, opted-in records, minimization principles require evaluating whether the full purchase history is actually necessary for the specific campaign or whether a smaller set of fields would achieve the same marketing purpose. 'Share the full purchase history regardless of campaign relevance' ignores the minimization obligation that applies independently of consent status. 'Purchase history is never shareable with any partner under any circumstance' is an overbroad absolute rule not supported by the facts; sharing may be appropriate if minimized and properly consented."},{"label":"What should govern this specific sharing arrangement going forward?","hint":"A documented, purpose-bound sharing agreement","options":["A documented data-sharing agreement specifying permitted use, retention, security, and prohibition on further redistribution by the partner","A verbal understanding between the marketing teams of both companies","No agreement is needed since both companies already have a business relationship"],"answer":0,"explain":"A documented data-sharing agreement that defines permitted use, retention limits, security requirements, and restrictions on further redistribution is the correct governance artifact for an ongoing third-party sharing arrangement. 'A verbal understanding between the marketing teams' provides no enforceable or auditable control over how the partner handles the data. 'No agreement is needed since both companies already have a business relationship' ignores that an existing general relationship does not substitute for purpose-specific data-sharing terms."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-18","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B2","title":"Selecting the IAM control for a privacy requirement","brief":"An internal HR application stores sensitive employee data, and the security architecture team must select the identity and access control that best enforces the privacy requirement that only an employee's own manager and HR can view their records.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ACCESS MODEL OPTIONS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>OPTION A:</span> All authenticated employees receive the same\n  broad \"HR-App-User\" role with read access to all employee records.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION B:</span> Role- and relationship-based access control\n  that grants visibility only to an employee's direct manager and\n  designated HR staff, scoped to that employee's own records.\n<span class='cy'>OPTION C:</span> No role distinctions; access is granted purely\n  based on which department created the account.","fields":[{"label":"Which option correctly enforces the stated privacy requirement?","hint":"Least privilege scoped to the specific relationship","options":["Option A","Option B","Option C"],"answer":1,"explain":"Option B implements least-privilege, relationship-scoped access so that only the specific manager and designated HR staff can view a given employee's own records, directly matching the stated requirement. 'Option A' grants broad read access to all records for every authenticated user, the opposite of the least-privilege requirement. 'Option C' bases access on account origin rather than actual need-to-know, failing to scope visibility appropriately at all."},{"label":"What IAM principle is Option A violating?","hint":"Access should map to need, not blanket membership","options":["Least privilege","Data minimization at rest","Encryption in transit"],"answer":0,"explain":"Granting every authenticated employee broad read access to all records violates least privilege, which requires access to be limited to what is necessary for a specific role or relationship. 'Data minimization at rest' concerns how much data is stored, not who can access it, so it is not the principle being violated here. 'Encryption in transit' concerns protecting data in motion, unrelated to the access-scoping problem described."},{"label":"After implementing Option B, what ongoing IAM control helps ensure access remains correctly scoped over time?","hint":"Roles and relationships change as people move","options":["Periodic access reviews/recertification tied to current manager and HR assignments","A one-time access grant at hire that never needs to be revisited","Removing all logging to reduce audit overhead"],"answer":0,"explain":"Periodic access reviews and recertification ensure that as employees change managers, roles, or leave the organization, access remains correctly scoped to the current, legitimate relationship. 'A one-time access grant at hire that never needs to be revisited' fails to account for organizational changes like reassignment or termination, quickly making access stale and excessive. 'Removing all logging to reduce audit overhead' actively undermines the ability to verify and audit access correctness, the opposite of a sound ongoing control."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-19","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4C3","title":"Choosing anonymization vs. pseudonymization","brief":"A data science team has three proposed uses for a customer dataset, and the privacy engineer must decide whether anonymization or pseudonymization is the appropriate technique for each.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DE-IDENTIFICATION REQUIREMENTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>USE 1:</span> Publish an aggregate public research report; no\n  future need to re-identify or link back to individuals.\n<span class='cy'>USE 2:</span> Run internal fraud analytics where investigators\n  must be able to re-link a flagged record back to the actual\n  customer for follow-up, under strict access controls.\n<span class='cy'>USE 3:</span> Share a dataset with an external research partner\n  where the partner must never be able to re-identify individuals,\n  even indirectly.","fields":[{"label":"Which technique fits USE 1?","hint":"No re-identification need at all, ever","options":["Pseudonymization","Anonymization","Tokenization with a reversible vault"],"answer":1,"explain":"Since the aggregate public report has no future need to re-identify individuals, true anonymization, irreversibly removing identifiability, is appropriate and also reduces the data outside personal-data scope for public release. 'Pseudonymization' retains a reversible link to identity, which is unnecessary risk for a public report with no re-identification need. 'Tokenization with a reversible vault' also preserves reversibility, which is not needed and adds unnecessary risk to a public release."},{"label":"Which technique fits USE 2?","hint":"Authorized re-linking is a functional requirement","options":["Anonymization","Pseudonymization, with the re-identification key protected under strict access controls","Sharing full plaintext identifiers with all investigators by default"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because investigators must be able to re-link a flagged record back to the customer, pseudonymization, replacing identifiers with tokens while protecting the mapping key under strict access controls, satisfies both the privacy and operational requirement. 'Anonymization' would make re-identification impossible even for legitimate investigators, defeating the fraud investigation's purpose. 'Sharing full plaintext identifiers with all investigators by default' unnecessarily exposes direct identifiers broadly, violating least-privilege and minimization principles."},{"label":"Which technique fits USE 3?","hint":"External partner, no re-identification possible even indirectly","options":["Pseudonymization with the key shared to the partner","Anonymization, since the partner must never be able to re-identify individuals even indirectly","Encryption in transit only, with identifiers left intact at rest"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because the external partner must never be able to re-identify individuals even indirectly, true anonymization is required; pseudonymization would leave a re-identification path if the key or auxiliary data were later available. 'Pseudonymization with the key shared to the partner' directly defeats the requirement by giving the partner the means to re-identify. 'Encryption in transit only, with identifiers left intact at rest' protects data in motion but leaves direct identifiers intact at rest, failing the no-re-identification requirement entirely."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-20","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4C5","title":"Selecting the right Privacy Enhancing Technology","brief":"An analytics team has four distinct technical requirements, and the privacy engineer must select the PET that best satisfies each one.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — PET SELECTION REQUIREMENTS","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQ 1:</span> Two banks want to jointly compute aggregate fraud\n  statistics across their combined transaction data without either\n  bank revealing its raw transaction records to the other.\n<span class='cy'>REQ 2:</span> A hospital wants to let researchers query a\n  patient database and receive statistically noisy, aggregate\n  results that protect any single patient from being singled out.\n<span class='cy'>REQ 3:</span> A payment processor wants to replace credit card\n  numbers in its systems with non-sensitive surrogate values while\n  preserving the ability to look up the original number in a\n  secure vault when absolutely necessary.","fields":[{"label":"Which PET best satisfies REQ 1?","hint":"Compute on encrypted or split data without revealing raw inputs","options":["Data masking","Secure multi-party computation (or homomorphic encryption)","Static data anonymization"],"answer":1,"explain":"Secure multi-party computation (or homomorphic encryption) allows multiple parties to jointly compute a result over their combined data without any party revealing its raw underlying records to the others, matching REQ 1 exactly. 'Data masking' simply obscures values for display and does not enable secure joint computation across organizations. 'Static data anonymization' removes identifiability from a single dataset but does not solve the cross-party joint-computation problem described."},{"label":"Which PET best satisfies REQ 2?","hint":"Calibrated statistical noise protects individuals in query results","options":["Differential privacy","Tokenization","Format-preserving encryption"],"answer":0,"explain":"Differential privacy adds calibrated statistical noise to query results so that no single patient's presence or absence can be discerned, exactly matching the requirement for protecting individuals in aggregate query outputs. 'Tokenization' replaces identifiers with tokens but does not add statistical noise to protect individuals within aggregate query results. 'Format-preserving encryption' preserves the format of data for system compatibility but does not address the statistical disclosure risk in aggregate queries."},{"label":"Which PET best satisfies REQ 3?","hint":"Reversible surrogate values with a secure lookup mechanism","options":["Differential privacy","Tokenization, with the mapping vault secured and access-controlled","Homomorphic encryption"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tokenization replaces sensitive values like credit card numbers with non-sensitive surrogate tokens while preserving a secure, access-controlled vault to reverse the mapping when genuinely necessary, matching REQ 3 precisely. 'Differential privacy' is designed for aggregate statistical query protection, not for reversible surrogate value substitution in transactional systems. 'Homomorphic encryption' enables computation on encrypted data but is not the standard fit for a reversible token/vault substitution pattern like this."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-21","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B6","title":"Applying encryption and key-management controls","brief":"A cloud architecture review must select the correct encryption and key-management approach for three components of a customer data platform.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ENCRYPTION ARCHITECTURE REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>COMPONENT 1:</span> Customer PII stored in a cloud database,\n  requiring protection from unauthorized access to the underlying\n  storage media or snapshots.\n<span class='cy'>COMPONENT 2:</span> API calls carrying customer PII between the\n  mobile app and the backend over public networks.\n<span class='cy'>COMPONENT 3:</span> Encryption keys currently stored in the same\n  cloud project and access tier as the data they protect, with no\n  rotation policy.","fields":[{"label":"What control addresses COMPONENT 1's requirement?","hint":"Protect data on the storage medium itself","options":["Encryption in transit only","Encryption at rest for the database and its snapshots","Hashing all fields with a fast, unsalted algorithm"],"answer":1,"explain":"Encryption at rest, applied to both the live database and its snapshots, protects PII from unauthorized access to the underlying storage media, directly matching COMPONENT 1's requirement. 'Encryption in transit only' protects data moving across networks, not data sitting on storage media or in snapshots. 'Hashing all fields with a fast, unsalted algorithm' is inappropriate for data that must remain retrievable in original form, and a fast unsalted hash is also weak and unsuitable for protecting sensitive stored values."},{"label":"What control addresses COMPONENT 2's requirement?","hint":"Protect data as it traverses public networks","options":["TLS (encryption in transit) between the app and backend","Encryption at rest for the mobile device's local cache only","No control is needed since mobile networks are inherently secure"],"answer":0,"explain":"TLS encrypts data in transit between the mobile app and backend, protecting customer PII as it crosses public networks, matching COMPONENT 2's requirement. 'Encryption at rest for the mobile device's local cache only' does not protect data actively moving across the network during the API call. 'No control is needed since mobile networks are inherently secure' is a false and dangerous assumption; public and carrier networks are not inherently secure for sensitive data in transit."},{"label":"What is the key issue with COMPONENT 3, and what should be done?","hint":"Keys should be separated from the data they protect and rotated","options":["No issue; storing keys alongside the data they protect is a security best practice","Keys stored with the data they protect, without rotation, undermine the value of encryption; separate key storage/management and implement a rotation policy","The only fix needed is to encrypt the keys themselves with the same key"],"answer":1,"explain":"Storing encryption keys in the same access tier as the data they protect, with no rotation, significantly weakens the protection encryption is supposed to provide, since a single compromise can expose both data and keys together; proper practice separates key storage (e.g., a dedicated key management service) and enforces periodic rotation. 'No issue; storing keys alongside the data they protect is a security best practice' is false and describes exactly the anti-pattern that undermines encryption's value. 'The only fix needed is to encrypt the keys themselves with the same key' is circular and does not solve the co-location or rotation problem at all."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-22","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B8","title":"Designing logging and monitoring for privacy assurance","brief":"A privacy engineer must specify what logging and monitoring controls are needed around a system that processes sensitive personal data, balancing detection needs against privacy risk from the logs themselves.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — LOGGING DESIGN REQUEST","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SYSTEM:</span> Customer support platform where agents can view\n  and edit full customer profiles, including sensitive data fields.\n<span class='cy'>CURRENT STATE:</span> No record exists of which agent viewed\n  or modified which customer's record, or when.\n<span class='cy'>PROPOSED LOG DESIGN:</span> Log every field's before/after value\n  in plaintext, including sensitive data, retained indefinitely.","fields":[{"label":"What is the core gap in the CURRENT STATE that must be fixed?","hint":"No accountability trail for access to sensitive data","options":["There is no audit trail of who accessed or modified sensitive customer records and when","The system has too many logging fields already","Agents have too little access to customer profiles"],"answer":0,"explain":"The absence of any record of who viewed or modified sensitive customer data, and when, is a fundamental gap in accountability and detective control that must be remediated with proper access and change logging. 'The system has too many logging fields already' contradicts the current state, which has no logging at all. 'Agents have too little access to customer profiles' is an access-scope concern, not the logging gap the scenario is asking about."},{"label":"What is the problem with the PROPOSED LOG DESIGN as written?","hint":"Logs themselves can become a new sensitive-data exposure","options":["It creates a second copy of sensitive data (in plaintext, retained indefinitely) that itself becomes a privacy risk requiring its own protection and retention limits","There is no problem; logging everything indefinitely is always the safest choice","Logging before/after values is technically impossible to implement"],"answer":0,"explain":"Logging full plaintext sensitive values indefinitely effectively duplicates the sensitive data into a new location, creating an additional attack surface and privacy risk that itself needs protection, minimization, and a defined retention limit. 'There is no problem; logging everything indefinitely is always the safest choice' ignores that the logs become a new repository of sensitive data requiring the same protections as the source system. 'Logging before/after values is technically impossible to implement' is factually incorrect; audit logging of field changes is a common and achievable control."},{"label":"How should the log design be revised to balance accountability with privacy risk?","hint":"Minimize what's logged in the clear, and bound retention","options":["Log the fact of access/modification and non-sensitive metadata, mask or omit sensitive field values in logs where feasible, apply access controls to the logs, and set a defined retention period","Remove all logging entirely to eliminate any risk from the logs","Log everything in plaintext but store it on a public shared drive for easy access by any employee"],"answer":0,"explain":"Logging the access/modification event and relevant metadata, masking sensitive field values where feasible, restricting who can view the logs, and applying a defined retention period balances the need for accountability with the privacy risk the logs themselves introduce. 'Remove all logging entirely' reintroduces the original accountability gap the design was meant to fix. 'Log everything in plaintext but store it on a public shared drive' massively increases exposure of sensitive data rather than protecting it."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-23","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4C1","title":"Implementing consent management and consent tagging","brief":"A marketing platform ingests customer records from multiple sources with different consent statuses, and the privacy engineer must ensure downstream systems respect each customer's actual consent state.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CONSENT DATA FLOW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>SOURCE A:</span> Customers who opted in to marketing emails only,\n  not SMS or partner sharing.\n<span class='cy'>SOURCE B:</span> Customers who opted in to marketing emails and\n  SMS, but explicitly opted out of partner sharing.\n<span class='cy'>CURRENT DESIGN:</span> All records are merged into one\n  marketing list with a single \"opted-in\" flag and no channel- or\n  purpose-specific detail.","fields":[{"label":"What is the flaw in the CURRENT DESIGN?","hint":"A single flag can't represent multiple, different consent choices","options":["A single generic \"opted-in\" flag cannot represent the distinct, channel- and purpose-specific consent choices each customer actually made","There is no flaw; a single flag is always sufficient for any consent scenario","The flaw is that too many source systems are being merged at all"],"answer":0,"explain":"Collapsing channel-specific and purpose-specific consent choices, email vs. SMS vs. partner sharing, into one generic flag loses the granularity needed to honor what each customer actually agreed to, risking unauthorized SMS messages or partner sharing. 'There is no flaw; a single flag is always sufficient' is incorrect precisely because the exhibit shows customers with materially different consent choices being flattened into one status. 'The flaw is that too many source systems are being merged at all' misidentifies the problem; merging sources is fine as long as consent granularity is preserved, which it currently is not."},{"label":"What should the consent-tagging design capture instead?","hint":"Purpose- and channel-specific granularity","options":["Only a binary yes/no for marketing overall, nothing more","Granular, purpose- and channel-specific consent tags (e.g., email: yes, SMS: yes/no, partner-sharing: yes/no) per customer record","The date the account was created, with no consent detail at all"],"answer":1,"explain":"Granular consent tags recorded per purpose and channel allow downstream systems to correctly suppress SMS or partner sharing for customers who did not consent to those specific uses, matching the actual choices made. 'Only a binary yes/no for marketing overall' repeats the exact flaw already identified, an oversimplified single flag. 'The date the account was created, with no consent detail at all' provides no actionable consent information whatsoever."},{"label":"What must downstream systems (e.g., the SMS gateway, the partner-sharing export) do with this improved tagging?","hint":"Enforce consent at the point of use","options":["Ignore the tags and send to the full merged list regardless","Filter/suppress recipients at the point of use based on the specific purpose- and channel-level consent tag relevant to that system","Only check consent once a year during an annual audit, with no real-time enforcement"],"answer":1,"explain":"Downstream systems must actively filter or suppress recipients at the point of use, checking the specific tag relevant to their channel or purpose, such as the SMS gateway checking the SMS tag, to ensure consent is honored in real time. 'Ignore the tags and send to the full merged list regardless' defeats the entire purpose of granular tagging. 'Only check consent once a year during an annual audit' would allow ongoing violations between audit cycles, since consent enforcement needs to happen at the moment of each use, not retrospectively."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-24","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4C2","title":"Managing tracking technologies and cookie consent","brief":"A website's cookie banner implementation must be evaluated against the stated requirement that non-essential tracking only occurs after affirmative, informed consent.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — COOKIE BANNER IMPLEMENTATION AUDIT","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>REQUIREMENT:</span> Non-essential cookies (analytics, ad\n  tracking) must not fire until the user gives affirmative,\n  informed consent; strictly necessary cookies are exempt.\n<span class='cy'>OBSERVED BEHAVIOR:</span> Analytics and ad-tracking scripts\n  load and set cookies immediately on page load, before the\n  banner is even displayed to the user.\n<span class='cy'>BANNER DESIGN:</span> A single \"Accept\" button; no way to\n  reject or customize by category, and the banner has no visible\n  close/reject option.","fields":[{"label":"Does the OBSERVED BEHAVIOR meet the stated requirement?","hint":"Scripts firing before consent is a hard compliance failure","options":["Yes, because the banner is shown eventually","No, because non-essential tracking cookies fire immediately on page load, before any consent is captured","Yes, as long as the cookies are deleted later if the user declines"],"answer":1,"explain":"Firing analytics and ad-tracking scripts immediately on page load, before the user ever sees or interacts with the consent banner, directly violates the requirement that non-essential tracking wait for prior affirmative consent. 'Yes, because the banner is shown eventually' ignores that the requirement is about firing order: consent must precede tracking, not simply exist somewhere on the page. 'Yes, as long as the cookies are deleted later if the user declines' does not cure the violation, since the tracking and data collection already occurred without consent before any deletion."},{"label":"What is the flaw in the BANNER DESIGN itself?","hint":"Consent must be a genuine, granular choice","options":["It offers only \"Accept\" with no reject or category-level option, which fails the requirement for informed, affirmative, and freely given consent","There is no flaw; a single Accept button is the simplest user experience","The flaw is that the banner is too visually prominent on the page"],"answer":0,"explain":"A banner offering only an \"Accept\" option, with no way to reject or choose by category, does not provide a genuine, freely given choice and fails informed-consent requirements that call for granularity and a real opportunity to decline. 'There is no flaw; a single Accept button is the simplest user experience' prioritizes simplicity over the legal requirement for a genuine, informed, and freely given choice. 'The flaw is that the banner is too visually prominent' is not a compliance issue at all and misses the actual defect, the missing reject/customize option."},{"label":"What is the correct technical remediation?","hint":"Gate script execution on consent, and offer real choice","options":["Gate all non-essential tracking scripts so they only execute after the user affirmatively opts in by category, and provide equally accessible accept/reject/customize options","Move the banner to the bottom of the page without changing script load behavior","Simply add more legal text to the banner without changing when scripts fire"],"answer":0,"explain":"The correct fix is a consent-management platform or equivalent mechanism that blocks non-essential scripts from executing until the user affirmatively opts in by category, paired with a banner offering equally accessible accept, reject, and customize options. 'Move the banner to the bottom of the page without changing script load behavior' does nothing to fix the core problem of scripts firing before consent. 'Simply add more legal text to the banner without changing when scripts fire' does not address the technical root cause, which is the script execution timing itself."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-25","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A5","title":"Embedding Privacy by Design into the SDLC","brief":"A development team is building a new feature and the privacy engineer must determine at which SDLC phase specific privacy activities belong, and evaluate a team's current practice.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SDLC PRIVACY INTEGRATION REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CURRENT PRACTICE:</span> Privacy review only happens at the\n  final \"security sign-off\" gate, one week before production release.\n<span class='cy'>FEATURE:</span> A new feature will collect a new category of\n  sensitive personal data (biometric voice patterns) not previously\n  processed by the company.\n<span class='cy'>FINDING AT SIGN-OFF:</span> The proposed data model stores raw\n  voice recordings indefinitely with no defined retention schedule\n  and no encryption at rest specified.","fields":[{"label":"What is the core Privacy by Design failure in the CURRENT PRACTICE?","hint":"Privacy considered only at the very end, not from the start","options":["Privacy requirements are considered only at the final gate rather than being embedded from the design phase onward","There is no failure; a final review is sufficient regardless of timing","The failure is that the review happened at all"],"answer":0,"explain":"Privacy by Design requires privacy requirements to be embedded from the earliest design phase, not bolted on at a final gate; reviewing only a week before release is the textbook opposite of Privacy by Design. 'There is no failure; a final review is sufficient regardless of timing' contradicts the Privacy by Design principle of proactive, early integration. 'The failure is that the review happened at all' is nonsensical; having a review is good, the failure is its late timing, not its existence."},{"label":"What should have happened earlier in the SDLC for this specific feature, given the new biometric data category?","hint":"New sensitive data category should trigger assessment before design finalizes","options":["A privacy/DPIA-style assessment and requirements-setting (retention schedule, encryption, minimization) during requirements/design, before the data model was finalized","Nothing different; biometric data is treated the same as any other field","Wait until after the first production incident to define retention and encryption requirements"],"answer":0,"explain":"Introducing a new sensitive data category like biometric voice patterns should trigger a privacy assessment and the setting of concrete requirements, retention schedule, encryption, minimization, during the requirements and design phase, before the data model is finalized. 'Nothing different; biometric data is treated the same as any other field' ignores that biometric data typically carries heightened legal and risk sensitivity requiring specific safeguards. 'Wait until after the first production incident' is a reactive approach that defeats the entire purpose of proactive Privacy by Design."},{"label":"Given the FINDING AT SIGN-OFF, what is the appropriate immediate action?","hint":"Fix the gaps before release, even if it affects the timeline","options":["Release as scheduled and fix retention/encryption in a later patch","Require the retention schedule and encryption-at-rest gaps to be remediated before release, even if it delays the launch","Ignore the finding since it was raised too late to matter"],"answer":1,"explain":"Given the gaps found, indefinite retention of raw biometric recordings with no encryption at rest, the appropriate action is to require remediation before release, even at the cost of delaying launch, since releasing with these gaps creates significant, avoidable privacy risk. 'Release as scheduled and fix retention/encryption in a later patch' knowingly ships a high-risk sensitive-data feature with unresolved gaps. 'Ignore the finding since it was raised too late to matter' abandons the entire purpose of the sign-off gate, which exists specifically to catch and address exactly this kind of finding before release."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-26","format":3,"domain":3,"obj":"3A4","title":"Resolving a data quality and accuracy gap","brief":"A customer disputes a credit decision, claiming the system used an outdated home address to calculate a regional risk score. The privacy/data governance team must determine the correct fix under data-quality obligations.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — DATA QUALITY INCIDENT","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>CUSTOMER CLAIM:</span> Moved 14 months ago; the risk-scoring\n  system still uses the prior address on file.\n<span class='cy'>ROOT CAUSE:</span> The address-change workflow only updates\n  the billing system; it never propagates to the risk-scoring\n  system, which has its own separate, unsynchronized copy.\n<span class='cy'>IMPACT:</span> The stale address caused an inaccurate regional\n  risk factor to be applied to this customer, and potentially others.","fields":[{"label":"What data-quality principle has been violated here?","hint":"Data must remain accurate and current for the purpose it's used for","options":["Data minimization","Accuracy — personal data used in a decision must be kept correct and up to date","Purpose limitation"],"answer":1,"explain":"The core failure is that data used to make a decision about the customer was stale and incorrect, which is squarely a violation of the accuracy principle requiring personal data to be kept correct and current for its purpose. 'Data minimization' concerns collecting no more data than necessary, which is not the issue described here. 'Purpose limitation' concerns using data only for compatible purposes, but the risk-scoring use is consistent with its original purpose; the problem is the data's correctness, not its use."},{"label":"What is the appropriate immediate remediation for this specific customer?","hint":"Correct the record and reassess the affected decision","options":["Correct the address in the risk-scoring system and re-run the risk assessment using accurate data","Tell the customer the score is final and cannot be revisited","Delete the customer's record entirely to avoid further disputes"],"answer":0,"explain":"The immediate fix is to correct the stale address in the risk-scoring system and re-run the assessment so the decision reflects accurate data, directly addressing the accuracy failure and its impact on this customer. 'Tell the customer the score is final and cannot be revisited' ignores the data subject's right to rectification and the organization's own accuracy obligation. 'Delete the customer's record entirely' is a disproportionate response that does not fix the decision and may violate other retention obligations."},{"label":"What systemic fix addresses the ROOT CAUSE for future customers?","hint":"Fix the propagation gap, not just this one record","options":["Nothing further is needed once this customer's address is corrected","Establish synchronization (or a single source of truth) so address changes propagate from the billing system to all downstream systems, including risk-scoring","Require customers to manually update every downstream system themselves"],"answer":1,"explain":"Since the root cause is those two systems never syncing, the systemic fix is to establish proper propagation, or a single authoritative source of truth, so an address update automatically reaches every downstream system that relies on it. 'Nothing further is needed once this customer's address is corrected' leaves the same propagation gap in place to affect other customers going forward. 'Require customers to manually update every downstream system themselves' unfairly shifts the organization's data-governance responsibility onto data subjects, who cannot be expected to know every internal system that holds their data."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-27","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4C7","title":"Assessing AI/ML privacy risk in a recommendation model","brief":"A data science team wants to deploy a customer-facing recommendation model, and the privacy engineer must evaluate specific technical risks unique to machine learning before approving the design.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — ML MODEL PRIVACY REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DESIGN NOTE 1:</span> The model was trained on a dataset that\n  included some customers who had exercised their erasure right\n  after training began, but before the model was finalized.\n<span class='cy'>DESIGN NOTE 2:</span> Researchers demonstrated a \"membership\n  inference\" style attack against a similar model, determining\n  whether a specific individual's data was in the training set.\n<span class='cy'>DESIGN NOTE 3:</span> The model's outputs will be used to make\n  automated pricing offers to individual customers with no human\n  review.","fields":[{"label":"What privacy issue does DESIGN NOTE 1 raise?","hint":"Erasure requests must actually take effect, including in trained models","options":["None; once training starts, erasure requests no longer apply","The erasure request may not have been honored if that customer's data remained in the training set used for the finalized model, risking a compliance gap","This only matters if the customer asks about it directly"],"answer":1,"explain":"If a customer's erasure request was made before the model was finalized but their data remained in the training set, the erasure may not have been effectively honored, creating a real compliance gap that must be investigated and remediated, potentially requiring retraining or other mitigations. 'None; once training starts, erasure requests no longer apply' incorrectly treats an in-progress training run as a shield against a valid erasure obligation. 'This only matters if the customer asks about it directly' is wrong because the obligation exists independent of whether the customer follows up."},{"label":"What privacy risk does DESIGN NOTE 2 illustrate, and what does it imply for this model?","hint":"Models can leak information about their own training data","options":["Membership inference risk, meaning the model itself could be probed to reveal whether specific individuals' data was used to train it, which should be assessed and mitigated (e.g., via differential privacy techniques)","No implication; membership inference only applies to the other team's model, never this one","This is purely a security bug unrelated to privacy"],"answer":0,"explain":"Membership inference demonstrates that trained models can leak information about their own training data, so this risk should be assessed for the new model too, with mitigations such as differential privacy training techniques considered. 'No implication; membership inference only applies to the other team's model' incorrectly assumes the risk is model-specific rather than a general risk class applicable to similar architectures and data. 'This is purely a security bug unrelated to privacy' mischaracterizes the issue; membership inference is fundamentally a privacy risk about individuals' data being inferred, not merely a generic security flaw."},{"label":"What does DESIGN NOTE 3 suggest should be evaluated before launch?","hint":"Automated decisions affecting individuals often carry extra obligations","options":["Nothing extra; automated pricing decisions require no additional privacy safeguards","Whether the applicable legal framework requires safeguards for solely automated decision-making with a significant effect on individuals (e.g., a right to human review, explanation, or contestability), and whether those safeguards are built in","Only whether the pricing model is profitable enough to justify the engineering cost"],"answer":1,"explain":"Solely automated decisions that significantly affect individuals, such as personalized pricing with no human review, often trigger specific legal safeguards like a right to obtain human review, an explanation, or to contest the decision, so this must be evaluated and built into the design before launch. 'Nothing extra; automated pricing decisions require no additional privacy safeguards' overlooks well-established legal protections around significant automated decisions. 'Only whether the pricing model is profitable enough to justify the engineering cost' is a business consideration entirely unrelated to the privacy and legal risk the note is raising."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-28","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4C8","title":"Evaluating privacy in an IoT/biometric device rollout","brief":"A company is rolling out smart office badges with biometric fingerprint readers for building access, and the privacy engineer must evaluate the technical design against privacy-by-design expectations for emerging technology.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — SMART BADGE DESIGN REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>DESIGN A:</span> Raw fingerprint images are captured, transmitted\n  unencrypted to a central server, and stored indefinitely alongside\n  employee names.\n<span class='cy'>DESIGN B:</span> A mathematical template (not the raw image) is\n  derived on-device, encrypted in transit and at rest, matched\n  locally where possible, with a defined retention tied to employment\n  status.\n<span class='cy'>DESIGN C:</span> Biometric data is shared with a third-party\n  building-management vendor with no contractual data protection terms.","fields":[{"label":"Which design best reflects privacy-engineering good practice for biometric data?","hint":"Minimize raw biometric exposure and bound retention","options":["Design A","Design B","Design C"],"answer":1,"explain":"Design B minimizes exposure by deriving a template instead of storing raw images, encrypts data in transit and at rest, favors local matching, and ties retention to a defined employment-status trigger, reflecting strong privacy-engineering practice for biometric data. 'Design A' transmits and stores raw biometric images unencrypted and indefinitely, maximizing both exposure and retention risk. 'Design C' shares sensitive biometric data with a third party with no contractual protections at all, a significant vendor-risk and compliance failure."},{"label":"What is the specific risk of DESIGN A's use of raw fingerprint images rather than a template?","hint":"Raw biometric data cannot be revoked or reissued like a password","options":["Raw images can be repurposed or misused far more broadly than a purpose-specific template, and unlike a password, a fingerprint cannot be reset if compromised","There is no additional risk; templates and raw images are functionally identical","Raw images are actually more secure because they are harder to fake"],"answer":0,"explain":"Raw fingerprint images retain full biometric detail that could be repurposed for other systems or misused if leaked, and because a person cannot change their fingerprint the way they can change a password, a raw-image compromise carries irreversible, lifelong risk. 'There is no additional risk; templates and raw images are functionally identical' is false, a template is a derived, purpose-limited representation with far less reuse potential than the raw image. 'Raw images are actually more secure because they are harder to fake' confuses spoof-resistance with data-protection risk, which are different concerns; the storage and misuse risk is what is being evaluated here."},{"label":"What must be in place before DESIGN C's third-party sharing could proceed responsibly?","hint":"Contractual and technical safeguards for a processor handling biometric data","options":["Nothing; sharing building-access data with a vendor is always low-risk","A data processing agreement with the vendor defining permitted use, security requirements, and retention, given the sensitivity of biometric data","Verbal assurance from the vendor's sales representative that the data will be handled safely"],"answer":1,"explain":"Given the heightened sensitivity of biometric data, a formal data processing agreement defining permitted use, security obligations, and retention/deletion requirements must be in place with the vendor before sharing proceeds responsibly. 'Nothing; sharing building-access data with a vendor is always low-risk' understates the sensitivity of biometric identifiers, which many laws treat as a special category of data. 'Verbal assurance from the vendor's sales representative' provides no enforceable or auditable protection for sensitive biometric data."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-29","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4B3","title":"Applying least-privilege authentication controls to a privacy system","brief":"A privacy team's case-management tool, used to process data-subject requests, currently has weak authentication and overly broad access, and the privacy engineer must recommend fixes.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — CASE-MANAGEMENT TOOL SECURITY REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDING 1:</span> All privacy team members share a single\n  generic login account for the case-management tool.\n<span class='cy'>FINDING 2:</span> The tool has only one permission level: any\n  logged-in user can view every open and closed DSAR case,\n  regardless of assignment.\n<span class='cy'>FINDING 3:</span> No multi-factor authentication is required,\n  despite the tool holding sensitive personal data from requests.","fields":[{"label":"What is the core problem with FINDING 1?","hint":"Individual accountability requires individual identity","options":["Shared accounts prevent attributing specific actions to a specific individual, undermining accountability and audit ability","Shared accounts are more efficient and should be encouraged elsewhere too","There is no problem, since all users are trusted privacy team members"],"answer":0,"explain":"A shared generic login makes it impossible to attribute who actually viewed or modified a specific case, which undermines accountability, complicates incident investigation, and violates the principle that access should be tied to individual identity. 'Shared accounts are more efficient and should be encouraged elsewhere too' promotes an anti-pattern that damages auditability wherever it is applied. 'There is no problem, since all users are trusted privacy team members' ignores that trust does not eliminate the need for individual accountability and traceability."},{"label":"What is the correct fix for FINDING 2?","hint":"Access should map to assignment, not blanket visibility","options":["Implement role- and assignment-based access so users see only the cases they are assigned to or have a legitimate need to view","Leave it as is, since the whole team works on privacy anyway","Add more users to the shared account to spread out the workload"],"answer":0,"explain":"Restricting visibility to cases a user is actually assigned to, or has a defined legitimate need to view, applies least privilege and reduces unnecessary exposure of sensitive DSAR case details across the team. 'Leave it as is, since the whole team works on privacy anyway' ignores least-privilege principles; shared team membership does not justify blanket access to every case regardless of assignment. 'Add more users to the shared account to spread out the workload' worsens FINDING 1's accountability problem rather than fixing the access-scope issue."},{"label":"Why is FINDING 3 particularly significant given what the tool contains?","hint":"Sensitive data warrants stronger authentication assurance","options":["Because the tool holds sensitive personal data from DSARs, a single-factor login creates disproportionate risk if credentials are phished or reused","MFA is never necessary for internal tools","Because MFA would slow down the privacy team too much to be worthwhile"],"answer":0,"explain":"Because the case-management tool holds sensitive personal data submitted through data-subject requests, relying on a single factor (password only) creates a disproportionate risk if credentials are phished, guessed, or reused, and MFA is a standard, proportionate control for this level of sensitivity. 'MFA is never necessary for internal tools' is a blanket claim that ignores risk-based control selection, especially for tools holding sensitive data. 'Because MFA would slow down the privacy team too much to be worthwhile' prioritizes convenience over a proportionate security control for a tool processing sensitive personal data."}]},
{"id":"PBQ-30","format":4,"domain":4,"obj":"4A6","title":"Reviewing API and cloud-native service privacy exposure","brief":"An internal API gateway review finds several issues in how a customer-facing API exposes personal data, and the privacy engineer must identify and prioritize the correct fixes.","exhibitTitle":"WORKPAPER — API PRIVACY REVIEW","exhibit":"<span class='cy'>FINDING A:</span> A \"get customer\" endpoint returns the entire\n  customer object, including fields the calling application never\n  displays or uses (e.g., full SSN, internal risk score).\n<span class='cy'>FINDING B:</span> The API has no rate limiting, allowing an\n  authenticated caller to enumerate sequential customer IDs and\n  retrieve records in bulk.\n<span class='cy'>FINDING C:</span> API access logs capture the full request and\n  response bodies, including personal data, with no masking.","fields":[{"label":"What principle does FINDING A violate, and what is the fix?","hint":"Return only what the consumer actually needs","options":["Least privilege / data minimization at the API layer; the fix is to return only the fields the calling application actually needs for its function","No principle is violated; returning full objects is simpler to maintain","The fix is to add more fields to the response for completeness"],"answer":0,"explain":"Returning an entire customer object, including sensitive fields the caller never uses, violates data minimization and least privilege at the API layer; the fix is to scope the response to only the fields the consuming application actually requires. 'No principle is violated; returning full objects is simpler to maintain' trades developer convenience for unnecessary exposure of highly sensitive fields like SSN. 'The fix is to add more fields to the response for completeness' moves in the wrong direction entirely, increasing rather than reducing unnecessary exposure."},{"label":"What privacy/security risk does FINDING B create, and what is the appropriate control?","hint":"Unbounded enumeration enables mass data harvesting","options":["Bulk enumeration and scraping risk; implement rate limiting, anomaly detection, and pagination/access controls to prevent mass extraction","No risk; authenticated callers are always trustworthy by definition","The fix is to remove authentication entirely to simplify the API"],"answer":0,"explain":"Without rate limiting, an authenticated but potentially compromised or malicious caller can enumerate sequential IDs to harvest large volumes of personal data; rate limiting, anomaly detection, and access controls on bulk patterns are the appropriate mitigations. 'No risk; authenticated callers are always trustworthy by definition' wrongly assumes authentication guarantees benign intent or that credentials can never be compromised or misused. 'The fix is to remove authentication entirely to simplify the API' would make the exposure dramatically worse by removing even the current access barrier."},{"label":"What is the appropriate fix for FINDING C?","hint":"Logs should not become an unprotected copy of sensitive payloads","options":["Mask or redact sensitive fields in logged request/response bodies, and apply strict access controls and retention limits to the logs themselves","No fix is needed; full-body logging is required for all debugging purposes permanently","Publish the logs to a shared internal wiki for easier troubleshooting"],"answer":0,"explain":"Masking or redacting sensitive fields before logging, combined with strict access controls and a defined retention limit on the logs, prevents the logging pipeline itself from becoming an unprotected secondary store of personal data. 'No fix is needed; full-body logging is required for all debugging purposes permanently' unnecessarily perpetuates a large, poorly protected copy of sensitive data with no bounded retention. 'Publish the logs to a shared internal wiki for easier troubleshooting' would dramatically widen access to sensitive personal data captured in the logs, the opposite of an appropriate fix."}]}
]);
